{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01L8cRCKis6agxDuL94F3jdn","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t000\n2\t001\n3\t002\n4\t003\n5\t004\n6\t005\n7\t006\n8\t007\n9\t008\n10\t009\n11\t010\n12\t011\n13\t012\n14\t013\n15\t014\n16\t015\n17\t016\n18\t017\n19\t018\n20\t019\n21\t020\n22\t021\n23\t022\n24\t023\n25\t024\n26\t025\n27\t026\n28\t027\n29\t028\n30\t029\n31\t030\n32\t031\n33\t032\n34\t033\n35\t034\n36\t035\n37\t036\n38\t037\n39\t038\n40\t039\n41\t040\n42\t041\n43\t042\n44\t043\n45\t044\n46\t045\n47\t046\n48\t047\n49\t048\n50\t049\n51\t050\n52\t051\n53\t052\n54\t053\n55\t054\n56\tSpiral RoPE\n57\t : Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\n58\tAnonymous Authors1\n59\tAbstract\n60\tRotary Position Embedding (RoPE) is the de facto\n61\tpositional encoding in large language models due\n62\tto its ability to encode relative positions and sup-\n63\tport length extrapolation. When adapted to vision\n64\ttransformers, the standard axial formulation de-\n65\tcomposes two-dimensional (2D) spatial positions\n66\tinto horizontal and vertical components, implic-\n67\titly restricting positional encoding to axis-aligned\n68\tdirections. We identify this directional constraint\n69\tas a fundamental limitation of the standard axial\n70\t2D RoPE, which hinders the modeling of oblique\n71\tspatial relationships that naturally exist in natu-\n72\tral images. To lift this limitation, we propose\n73\tSpiral RoPE, a simple yet effective extension\n74\tthat enables multi-directional positional encoding\n75\tby partitioning embedding channels into multi-\n76\tple groups associated with uniformly distributed\n77\tdirections. Each group is rotated according to\n78\tthe projection of the patch position onto its corre-\n79\tsponding direction, allowing spatial relationships\n80\tto be encoded beyond the horizontal and verti-\n81\tcal axes. Across a wide range of vision tasks\n82\tincluding classification, segmentation, and gen-\n83\teration, Spiral RoPE consistently improves per-\n84\tformance. Qualitative analysis of attention maps\n85\tfurther show that Spiral RoPE exhibits more con-\n86\tcentrated activations on semantically relevant ob-\n87\tjects and better respects local object boundaries,\n88\thighlighting the importance of multi-directional\n89\tpositional encoding in vision transformers.\n90\t1. Introduction\n91\tRotary Position Embedding (RoPE) (?) has become a\n92\tcornerstone of modern language transformers, powering\n93\tstate-of-the-art large language models such as the LLaMA\n94\tseries (???) and Qwen series (????). By encoding po-\n95\t1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\n96\tAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n97\t<anon.email@domain.com>.\n98\tPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\n99\ton Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\n100\t1.0\n101\t 0.5\n102\t 0.0 0.5 1.0\n103\tx\n104\t1.0\n105\t0.5\n106\t0.0\n107\t0.5\n108\t1.0\n109\ty\n110\tTraditional 2D Axial RoPE\n111\t(all ±  on 0° and 90° axes)\n112\t1.0\n113\t 0.5\n114\t 0.0 0.5 1.0\n115\tx\n116\tOur Spiral RoPE (K=8)\n117\t(pairs assigned to = g 90/rotate and + 90)\n118\tFigure 1.Frequency support visualizationcomparing Axial 2D\n119\tRoPE(left)and Spiral RoPE(right)with eight rotation groups\n120\t(K= 8 ). As shown, the Axial 2D RoPE places all frequencies on\n121\thorizontal and vertical axes only, while our Spiral RoPE distributes\n122\tfrequencies across multiple directions in a spiral pattern, offering\n123\ta broader directional coverage.\n124\tsitional information through rotation operations on query\n125\tand key vectors, RoPE naturally captures relative positions\n126\tand enables effective length extrapolation. Such proper-\n127\tties have been proven essential for scaling transformers to\n128\tlong contexts. In contrast, standard Vision Transformers\n129\t(ViTs) (?) predominantly rely on absolute positional em-\n130\tbeddings (APE), which encode fixed position vectors that\n131\tare added to patch embeddings. While simple and effec-\n132\ttive, APE has well-documented limitations: it struggles to\n133\tgeneralize to resolutions unseen during training and pro-\n134\tvides no explicit mechanism for encoding relative spatial\n135\trelationships between image patches.\n136\tRecent work has begun exploring RoPE for vision\n137\ttasks (???), demonstrating promising results on image clas-\n138\tsification, dense prediction, and generation tasks. The stan-\n139\tdard approach extends 1D RoPE to 2D images by decompos-\n140\ting spatial positions into horizontal and vertical components.\n141\tWe term this approach asAxial 2D RoPE. Half of the em-\n142\tbedding dimensions are rotated based on the x-coordinate,\n143\twhile the other half uses the y-coordinate. However, this\n144\taxial decomposition inherits a fundamental limitation: it can\n145\tonly encode positional relationships along the coordinate\n146\taxes. when we visualize the frequency support of Axial\n147\t2D RoPE in the 2D Fourier domain, all frequencies lie ex-\n148\tclusively on the horizontal and vertical axes. This means\n149\tAxial 2D RoPE is insensitive to positional changes along\n150\tdiagonal or other oblique directions, which is a limitation\n151\tgiven that natural images contain rich spatial structures in\n152\tall orientations. To demonstrate this limitation concretely,\n153\twe perform a Fourier reconstruction experiment in Figure 2:\n154\t1\n155\t055\n156\t056\n157\t057\n158\t058\n159\t059\n160\t060\n161\t061\n162\t062\n163\t063\n164\t064\n165\t065\n166\t066\n167\t067\n168\t068\n169\t069\n170\t070\n171\t071\n172\t072\n173\t073\n174\t074\n175\t075\n176\t076\n177\t077\n178\t078\n179\t079\n180\t080\n181\t081\n182\t082\n183\t083\n184\t084\n185\t085\n186\t086\n187\t087\n188\t088\n189\t089\n190\t090\n191\t091\n192\t092\n193\t093\n194\t094\n195\t095\n196\t096\n197\t097\n198\t098\n199\t099\n200\t100"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e05e2ee8-2a48-4730-8e68-8246ab911fe5","uuid":"7d46ea79-5067-4220-b756-12436cb6933d","timestamp":"2026-04-26T19:34:16.895Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/papers/spiralrope.txt","content":"000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nSpiral RoPE\n : Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nRotary Position Embedding (RoPE) is the de facto\npositional encoding in large language models due\nto its ability to encode relative positions and sup-\nport length extrapolation. When adapted to vision\ntransformers, the standard axial formulation de-\ncomposes two-dimensional (2D) spatial positions\ninto horizontal and vertical components, implic-\nitly restricting positional encoding to axis-aligned\ndirections. We identify this directional constraint\nas a fundamental limitation of the standard axial\n2D RoPE, which hinders the modeling of oblique\nspatial relationships that naturally exist in natu-\nral images. To lift this limitation, we propose\nSpiral RoPE, a simple yet effective extension\nthat enables multi-directional positional encoding\nby partitioning embedding channels into multi-\nple groups associated with uniformly distributed\ndirections. Each group is rotated according to\nthe projection of the patch position onto its corre-\nsponding direction, allowing spatial relationships\nto be encoded beyond the horizontal and verti-\ncal axes. Across a wide range of vision tasks\nincluding classification, segmentation, and gen-\neration, Spiral RoPE consistently improves per-\nformance. Qualitative analysis of attention maps\nfurther show that Spiral RoPE exhibits more con-\ncentrated activations on semantically relevant ob-\njects and better respects local object boundaries,\nhighlighting the importance of multi-directional\npositional encoding in vision transformers.\n1. Introduction\nRotary Position Embedding (RoPE) (?) has become a\ncornerstone of modern language transformers, powering\nstate-of-the-art large language models such as the LLaMA\nseries (???) and Qwen series (????). By encoding po-\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\n1.0\n 0.5\n 0.0 0.5 1.0\nx\n1.0\n0.5\n0.0\n0.5\n1.0\ny\nTraditional 2D Axial RoPE\n(all ±  on 0° and 90° axes)\n1.0\n 0.5\n 0.0 0.5 1.0\nx\nOur Spiral RoPE (K=8)\n(pairs assigned to = g 90/rotate and + 90)\nFigure 1.Frequency support visualizationcomparing Axial 2D\nRoPE(left)and Spiral RoPE(right)with eight rotation groups\n(K= 8 ). As shown, the Axial 2D RoPE places all frequencies on\nhorizontal and vertical axes only, while our Spiral RoPE distributes\nfrequencies across multiple directions in a spiral pattern, offering\na broader directional coverage.\nsitional information through rotation operations on query\nand key vectors, RoPE naturally captures relative positions\nand enables effective length extrapolation. Such proper-\nties have been proven essential for scaling transformers to\nlong contexts. In contrast, standard Vision Transformers\n(ViTs) (?) predominantly rely on absolute positional em-\nbeddings (APE), which encode fixed position vectors that\nare added to patch embeddings. While simple and effec-\ntive, APE has well-documented limitations: it struggles to\ngeneralize to resolutions unseen during training and pro-\nvides no explicit mechanism for encoding relative spatial\nrelationships between image patches.\nRecent work has begun exploring RoPE for vision\ntasks (???), demonstrating promising results on image clas-\nsification, dense prediction, and generation tasks. The stan-\ndard approach extends 1D RoPE to 2D images by decompos-\ning spatial positions into horizontal and vertical components.\nWe term this approach asAxial 2D RoPE. Half of the em-\nbedding dimensions are rotated based on the x-coordinate,\nwhile the other half uses the y-coordinate. However, this\naxial decomposition inherits a fundamental limitation: it can\nonly encode positional relationships along the coordinate\naxes. when we visualize the frequency support of Axial\n2D RoPE in the 2D Fourier domain, all frequencies lie ex-\nclusively on the horizontal and vertical axes. This means\nAxial 2D RoPE is insensitive to positional changes along\ndiagonal or other oblique directions, which is a limitation\ngiven that natural images contain rich spatial structures in\nall orientations. To demonstrate this limitation concretely,\nwe perform a Fourier reconstruction experiment in Figure 2:\n1\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100","numLines":200,"startLine":1,"totalLines":1705}}}
