{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011EqA6vWubsSbPseQRHAhRD","type":"tool_result","content":"750\tWe use K= 16 directions for Spiral RoPE with all frequen-\n751\tcies θt scaled by a factor of 1.5 (i.e., θt = 1.5θ −t/(d/4)\n752\tbase ).\n753\tModels are pre-trained at 224×224 resolution for 300\n754\tepochs (Small and Base) or 200 epochs (Large), then fine-\n755\ttuned at the target resolution for 20 epochs. We compare\n756\tagainst the standard DeiT baseline and RoPE-Mixed (?),\n757\twhich uses learnable per-head frequencies, in contrast to\n758\tour method that uses pre-specified directions and frequen-\n759\tcies. For evaluation, we report Top-1 accuracy on the valida-\n760\ttion set using the final checkpoint with exponential moving\n761\taverage (EMA) weights and full crop (crop ratio = 1.0).\n762\tAdditional training details are provided in Appendix A.\n763\tResults.Table 1 presents the classification results across\n764\tdifferent resolutions. Spiral RoPE consistently outperforms\n765\tboth the APE baseline and RoPE-Mixed across all configu-\n766\trations. These results demonstrate that the multi-directional\n767\tencoding in Spiral RoPE provides richer positional informa-\n768\ttion that benefits image classification, with larger improve-\n769\tments observed at higher resolutions.\n770\tExtrapolation Robustness.We further evaluate robust-\n771\tness to input resolutions unseen during training. Using mod-\n772\tels trained and fine-tuned at 224×224 resolution, we evalu-\n773\tate performance across resolutions ranging from 144×144\n774\tto 512×512 . Other evaluation settings are the same as\n775\tbefore. For resolution extrapolation, APE employs bicu-\n776\tbic interpolation to resize the learned position vectors from\n777\ttraining to evaluation resolution. RoPE-based methods ex-\n778\ttend position indices to the new grid size while preserving\n779\tthe same frequency patterns, enabling smooth extrapolation\n780\tthrough the inherent continuity of trigonometric functions.\n781\t5\n782\t275\n783\t276\n784\t277\n785\t278\n786\t279\n787\t280\n788\t281\n789\t282\n790\t283\n791\t284\n792\t285\n793\t286\n794\t287\n795\t288\n796\t289\n797\t290\n798\t291\n799\t292\n800\t293\n801\t294\n802\t295\n803\t296\n804\t297\n805\t298\n806\t299\n807\t300\n808\t301\n809\t302\n810\t303\n811\t304\n812\t305\n813\t306\n814\t307\n815\t308\n816\t309\n817\t310\n818\t311\n819\t312\n820\t313\n821\t314\n822\t315\n823\t316\n824\t317\n825\t318\n826\t319\n827\t320\n828\t321\n829\t322\n830\t323\n831\t324\n832\t325\n833\t326\n834\t327\n835\t328\n836\t329\n837\tSpiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\n838\tTable 1.ImageNet-1k classification accuracy (%).Models are pre-\n839\ttrained at 224×224 and fine-tuned at each target resolution. Spiral\n840\tRoPE consistently outperforms baselines across all configurations.\n841\tMODELMETHOD224 384 448\n842\tDEIT-S\n843\tAPE 79.11 81.88 82.24\n844\tROPE-MIXED80.4882.64 82.99\n845\tSPIRALROPE (OURS) 80.3983.04 83.15\n846\tDEIT-B\n847\tAPE 82.36 84.16 84.29\n848\tROPE-MIXED83.15 84.73 84.84\n849\tSPIRALROPE (OURS)83.39 85.04 85.19\n850\tDEIT-L\n851\tAPE 83.24 84.92 85.13\n852\tROPE-MIXED83.51 85.14 85.40\n853\tSPIRALROPE (OURS)83.97 85.48 85.67\n854\tFigure 4 shows the extrapolation robustness results for both\n855\tDeiT-Base and DeiT-Large models. Both Spiral RoPE and\n856\tRoPE-Mixed consistently outperform APE across all res-\n857\tolutions and model sizes, demonstrating the advantage of\n858\trotary position embeddings for resolution generalization. At\n859\tlower resolutions near the training resolution, Spiral RoPE\n860\tand RoPE-Mixed perform comparably. However, at higher\n861\tresolutions (e.g., 384×384 to 512×512 ), our Spiral RoPE\n862\texhibits a clear advantage over RoPE-Mixed across both\n863\tmodel sizes, suggesting that our method with pre-specified\n864\tdirections and fixed sinusoidal frequencies achieves better\n865\textrapolation than RoPE-Mixed with learned frequencies\n866\twhen evaluating on unseen resolutions.\n867\t4.2. Semantic Segmentation\n868\tSetup.We evaluate Spiral RoPE on semantic segmenta-\n869\ttion using the ADE20k dataset (??), which contains 20,000\n870\ttraining images and 2,000 validation images across 150\n871\tsemantic categories. We use UperNet (?) as the segmen-\n872\ttation framework with ViT training recipe, and we initial-\n873\tize the backbone with the ImageNet pre-trained weights at\n874\t224×224. The segmentation models are trained at512×512\n875\tresolution for 160k iterations with a batch size of 16. For\n876\tevaluation, we perform single-scale testing on the validation\n877\tset and report mean Intersection over Union (mIoU), mean\n878\tclass accuracy (mAcc), and overall pixel accuracy (aAcc).\n879\tAdditional training details are provided in Appendix A.\n880\tResults.Table 2 summarizes semantic segmentation re-\n881\tsults on ADE20k, where Spiral RoPE consistently achieves\n882\tsignificant improvements over the original APE baselines.\n883\tRemarkably, we observe that the DeiT-Large model attains\n884\ta notable mIoU of 49.12%, substantially outperforming\n885\tthe original baseline of 46.91% at virtually no additional\n886\tcomputational cost. Moreover, the gains brought by Spi-\n887\tral RoPE on the ADE20K semantic segmentation task are\n888\tintuitively more pronounced than those observed in clas-\n889\tsification (e.g., 3.06% vs. 0.73% accuracy improvement),\n890\t144 192 224 256 320 384 448 512\n891\tInput resolution\n892\t76\n893\t78\n894\t80\n895\t82\n896\t84T op-1 Accuracy (%)\n897\tTraining resolution\n898\tMulti-resolution performance (T op-1 Acc)\n899\tAPE\n900\tRoPE-Mixed\n901\tSpiral RoPE (ours)\n902\t(a)DeiT-Base\n903\t144 192 224 256 320 384 448 512\n904\tInput resolution\n905\t78\n906\t80\n907\t82\n908\t84T op-1 Accuracy (%)\n909\tTraining resolution\n910\tMulti-resolution performance (T op-1 Acc)\n911\tAPE\n912\tRoPE-Mixed\n913\tSpiral RoPE (ours)\n914\t(b)DeiT-Large\n915\tFigure 4.Multi-resolution performance on ImageNet-1k. Models\n916\tare trained at 224×224 and evaluated across resolutions from\n917\t144×144 to 512×512 . Spiral RoPE demonstrates superior\n918\trobustness to resolution changes compared to APE and RoPE-\n919\tMixed baselines across both model sizes.\n920\tTable 2.ADE20k semantic segmentation results.All models are\n921\tpretrained on ImageNet-1k and then fintuned with an UperNet\n922\tsegmentation head for 160k iterations at512×512resolution.\n923\tBACKBONEMETHOD MIOUMACC AACC\n924\tDEIT-S APE 43.72 54.33 81.07\n925\tSPIRALROPE45.44 56.33 81.61\n926\tDEIT-B APE 46.89 57.28 82.30\n927\tSPIRALROPE48.11 59.07 82.76\n928\tDEIT-L APE 46.91 57.05 82.36\n929\tSPIRALROPE49.12 60.11 83.40\n930\tsuggesting that for dense prediction tasks such as semantic\n931\tsegmentation where reasoning is more complex and higher\n932\tinput resolutions are required, a well-designed relative posi-\n933\ttion embedding can more effectively facilitate the modeling\n934\tof spatial dependencies, demonstrating that Spiral RoPE\n935\tconsistently delivers larger benefits on more challenging\n936\ttasks.\n937\t4.3. Image Generation\n938\tSetup.We also evaluate Spiral RoPE on class-conditional\n939\timage generation using Diffusion Transformers (DiT) (?).\n940\tWe train DiT models of various sizes (S, B, L, XL) with\n941\tpatch sizes of 2 (denoted as /2 in the original paper) on Ima-\n942\tgeNet 256×256 . The /2 models process 128×128 latent\n943\tpatches (16×16 tokens after patchification). We useK= 8\n944\t6\n945\t330\n946\t331\n947\t332\n948\t333\n949\t334\n950\t335\n951\t336\n952\t337\n953\t338\n954\t339\n955\t340\n956\t341\n957\t342\n958\t343\n959\t344\n960\t345\n961\t346\n962\t347\n963\t348\n964\t349\n965\t350\n966\t351\n967\t352\n968\t353\n969\t354\n970\t355\n971\t356\n972\t357\n973\t358\n974\t359\n975\t360\n976\t361\n977\t362\n978\t363\n979\t364\n980\t365\n981\t366\n982\t367\n983\t368\n984\t369\n985\t370\n986\t371\n987\t372\n988\t373\n989\t374\n990\t375\n991\t376\n992\t377\n993\t378\n994\t379\n995\t380\n996\t381\n997\t382\n998\t383\n999\t384\n1000\tSpiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\n1001\tTable 3.Class-conditional image generationon ImageNet 256×\n1002\t256 using DiT. We compare models trained for 400k steps with\n1003\tthe standard training hyperparameters of DiT. We generate 50k\n1004\tsamples using DDPM sampling with 250 steps and classifier-free\n1005\tguidance scale of 1.0. Baseline results with supermarks * are taken\n1006\tfrom U-DiTs (?).\n1007\tMODELMETHODFID↓SFID↓IS↑PREC.↑REC.↑\n1008\tDIT-S/2 APE∗ 67.40 11.93 20.44 0.368 0.559\n1009\tSPIRALROPE63.33 11.91 21.96 0.386 0.574\n1010\tDIT-B/2 APE∗ 42.84 8.24 33.66 0.491 0.629\n1011\tSPIRALROPE37.74 8.23 38.31 0.520 0.630\n1012\tDIT-L/2 APE∗ 23.276.3559.63 0.6110.635\n1013\tSPIRALROPE19.026.3669.49 0.6380.632\n1014\tDIT-XL/2 APE∗ 20.05 6.25 66.74 0.632 0.629\n1015\tSPIRALROPE15.55 5.87 79.67 0.662 0.631\n1016\tTable 4.Extended training comparisonon ImageNet256×256.\n1017\tThe Spiral RoPE model uses DiT-XL/2 architecture trained for\n1018\t7M steps. We use classifier-free guidance with scale 1.5. Baseline\n1019\tresults are from SiT (?).\n1020\tMETHODFID↓SFID↓IS↑PREC.↑REC.↑\n1021\tDIT 2.27 4.60 278.24 0.83 0.57\n1022\tSIT 2.06 4.49 277.50 0.83 0.59\n1023\tSPIRALROPE (OURS)1.74 4.49 279.64 0.83 0.60\n1024\tdirections for S/B/L models and K= 6 for XL models. All\n1025\tmodels are trained for 400k steps with the original training\n1026\trecipe of DiT (?). For evaluation, we generate 50k samples\n1027\tusing DDPM sampling with 250 steps and classifier-free\n1028\tguidance scale of 1.0, and compute Fr´echet Inception Dis-\n1029\ttance (FID) (?) against the ImageNet validation set statistics.\n1030\tAdditional training details are provided in Appendix A.\n1031\tResults.Table 3 presents the FID scores. The results sug-\n1032\tgest that Spiral RoPE is most effective when the sequence\n1033\tlength is sufficiently large for the multi-directional encoding\n1034\tto capture meaningful spatial relationships.\n1035\tExtended Training.To further demonstrate the effective-\n1036\tness of Spiral RoPE when scaled to longer training, we\n1037\tconduct experiments following the setup of SiT (?). Specif-\n1038\tically, we train the XL/2 models for 7 million steps on\n1039\tImageNet 256×256 and evaluate using classifier-free guid-\n1040\tance with scale 1.5. Table 4 compares our Spiral RoPE\n1041\tagainst the original DiT baseline and SiT. Our Spiral RoPE\n1042\tachieves an FID of 1.74, outperforming both DiT (2.27) and\n1043\tSiT (2.06). Figure 5 shows qualitative samples generated by\n1044\tour model.\n1045\t5. Analysis\n1046\tIn this section, we provide further analysis of Spiral RoPE,\n1047\tincluding visualization of attention maps and ablation stud-\n1048\tFigure 5.Generated samplesfrom our DiT-XL/2 model with\n1049\tSpiral RoPE trained for 7M steps on ImageNet 256×256 . Images\n1050\tare generated using classifier-free guidance with scale 4.0.\n1051\ties on key hyperparameters.\n1052\t5.1. Visualization of Attention Maps\n1053\tTo qualitatively understand the differences between posi-\n1054\ttional encoding methods, we visualize attention maps from\n1055\tDeiT-Base models fine-tuned at448×448 resolution. We\n1056\tcompare three variants: the original APE baseline, APE\n1057\twith axial 2D RoPE, and APE with Spiral RoPE (K= 16 ).\n1058\tClass-Token Attention.We first visualize the class-token\n1059\tattention by averaging the attention weights over all heads\n1060\tin the last transformer layer. Figure 6 shows representative\n1061\texamples from the ImageNet validation set. A clear progres-\n1062\tsion is visible across the three methods. The APE baseline\n1063\tproduces diffuse attention patterns, with substantial activa-\n1064\ttion spread across both foreground objects and background\n1065\tregions. Axial RoPE improves over APE by allocating\n1066\tstronger attention to semantically relevant regions; however,\n1067\tits attention maps still exhibit noticeable residual activations\n1068\tin surrounding background areas and irrelevant objects. In\n1069\tcontrast, Spiral RoPE yields the most object-centric and\n1070\tspatially coherent attention patterns, characterized by con-\n1071\tcentrated responses on the foreground objects and effective\n1072\tsuppression of background activations. This advantage is\n1073\tparticularly pronounced in multi-instance scenes, where Spi-\n1074\tral RoPE sharply attends to multiple relevant objects, while\n1075\tAxial RoPE still exhibits axis-aligned artifacts and attention\n1076\tleakage into nearby regions.\n1077\tQuery-Token Attention.To further examine how posi-\n1078\ttional encoding influences local spatial relationships, we vi-\n1079\tsualize attention patterns originating from individual patch\n1080\ttokens. Figure 3 shows representative examples in which\n1081\tthe query token (marked by a red box) is located on a fore-\n1082\t7\n1083\t385\n1084\t386\n1085\t387\n1086\t388\n1087\t389\n1088\t390\n1089\t391\n1090\t392\n1091\t393\n1092\t394\n1093\t395\n1094\t396\n1095\t397\n1096\t398\n1097\t399\n1098\t400\n1099\t401\n1100\t402\n1101\t403\n1102\t404\n1103\t405\n1104\t406\n1105\t407\n1106\t408\n1107\t409\n1108\t410\n1109\t411\n1110\t412\n1111\t413\n1112\t414\n1113\t415\n1114\t416\n1115\t417\n1116\t418\n1117\t419\n1118\t420\n1119\t421\n1120\t422\n1121\t423\n1122\t424\n1123\t425\n1124\t426\n1125\t427\n1126\t428\n1127\t429\n1128\t430\n1129\t431\n1130\t432\n1131\t433\n1132\t434\n1133\t435\n1134\t436\n1135\t437\n1136\t438\n1137\t439\n1138\tSpiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\n1139\tImage Input\n1140\t APE (original)\n1141\t Axial RoPE\n1142\t Spiral RoPE (ours)\n1143\tImage Input\n1144\t APE (original)\n1145\t Axial RoPE\n1146\t Spiral RoPE (ours)\n1147\tImage Input\n1148\t APE (original)\n1149\t Axial RoPE"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e05e2ee8-2a48-4730-8e68-8246ab911fe5","uuid":"064482fb-171f-46e4-a91e-9723f6b261c9","timestamp":"2026-04-26T19:34:21.614Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/papers/spiralrope.txt","content":"We use K= 16 directions for Spiral RoPE with all frequen-\ncies θt scaled by a factor of 1.5 (i.e., θt = 1.5θ −t/(d/4)\nbase ).\nModels are pre-trained at 224×224 resolution for 300\nepochs (Small and Base) or 200 epochs (Large), then fine-\ntuned at the target resolution for 20 epochs. We compare\nagainst the standard DeiT baseline and RoPE-Mixed (?),\nwhich uses learnable per-head frequencies, in contrast to\nour method that uses pre-specified directions and frequen-\ncies. For evaluation, we report Top-1 accuracy on the valida-\ntion set using the final checkpoint with exponential moving\naverage (EMA) weights and full crop (crop ratio = 1.0).\nAdditional training details are provided in Appendix A.\nResults.Table 1 presents the classification results across\ndifferent resolutions. Spiral RoPE consistently outperforms\nboth the APE baseline and RoPE-Mixed across all configu-\nrations. These results demonstrate that the multi-directional\nencoding in Spiral RoPE provides richer positional informa-\ntion that benefits image classification, with larger improve-\nments observed at higher resolutions.\nExtrapolation Robustness.We further evaluate robust-\nness to input resolutions unseen during training. Using mod-\nels trained and fine-tuned at 224×224 resolution, we evalu-\nate performance across resolutions ranging from 144×144\nto 512×512 . Other evaluation settings are the same as\nbefore. For resolution extrapolation, APE employs bicu-\nbic interpolation to resize the learned position vectors from\ntraining to evaluation resolution. RoPE-based methods ex-\ntend position indices to the new grid size while preserving\nthe same frequency patterns, enabling smooth extrapolation\nthrough the inherent continuity of trigonometric functions.\n5\n275\n276\n277\n278\n279\n280\n281\n282\n283\n284\n285\n286\n287\n288\n289\n290\n291\n292\n293\n294\n295\n296\n297\n298\n299\n300\n301\n302\n303\n304\n305\n306\n307\n308\n309\n310\n311\n312\n313\n314\n315\n316\n317\n318\n319\n320\n321\n322\n323\n324\n325\n326\n327\n328\n329\nSpiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\nTable 1.ImageNet-1k classification accuracy (%).Models are pre-\ntrained at 224×224 and fine-tuned at each target resolution. Spiral\nRoPE consistently outperforms baselines across all configurations.\nMODELMETHOD224 384 448\nDEIT-S\nAPE 79.11 81.88 82.24\nROPE-MIXED80.4882.64 82.99\nSPIRALROPE (OURS) 80.3983.04 83.15\nDEIT-B\nAPE 82.36 84.16 84.29\nROPE-MIXED83.15 84.73 84.84\nSPIRALROPE (OURS)83.39 85.04 85.19\nDEIT-L\nAPE 83.24 84.92 85.13\nROPE-MIXED83.51 85.14 85.40\nSPIRALROPE (OURS)83.97 85.48 85.67\nFigure 4 shows the extrapolation robustness results for both\nDeiT-Base and DeiT-Large models. Both Spiral RoPE and\nRoPE-Mixed consistently outperform APE across all res-\nolutions and model sizes, demonstrating the advantage of\nrotary position embeddings for resolution generalization. At\nlower resolutions near the training resolution, Spiral RoPE\nand RoPE-Mixed perform comparably. However, at higher\nresolutions (e.g., 384×384 to 512×512 ), our Spiral RoPE\nexhibits a clear advantage over RoPE-Mixed across both\nmodel sizes, suggesting that our method with pre-specified\ndirections and fixed sinusoidal frequencies achieves better\nextrapolation than RoPE-Mixed with learned frequencies\nwhen evaluating on unseen resolutions.\n4.2. Semantic Segmentation\nSetup.We evaluate Spiral RoPE on semantic segmenta-\ntion using the ADE20k dataset (??), which contains 20,000\ntraining images and 2,000 validation images across 150\nsemantic categories. We use UperNet (?) as the segmen-\ntation framework with ViT training recipe, and we initial-\nize the backbone with the ImageNet pre-trained weights at\n224×224. The segmentation models are trained at512×512\nresolution for 160k iterations with a batch size of 16. For\nevaluation, we perform single-scale testing on the validation\nset and report mean Intersection over Union (mIoU), mean\nclass accuracy (mAcc), and overall pixel accuracy (aAcc).\nAdditional training details are provided in Appendix A.\nResults.Table 2 summarizes semantic segmentation re-\nsults on ADE20k, where Spiral RoPE consistently achieves\nsignificant improvements over the original APE baselines.\nRemarkably, we observe that the DeiT-Large model attains\na notable mIoU of 49.12%, substantially outperforming\nthe original baseline of 46.91% at virtually no additional\ncomputational cost. Moreover, the gains brought by Spi-\nral RoPE on the ADE20K semantic segmentation task are\nintuitively more pronounced than those observed in clas-\nsification (e.g., 3.06% vs. 0.73% accuracy improvement),\n144 192 224 256 320 384 448 512\nInput resolution\n76\n78\n80\n82\n84T op-1 Accuracy (%)\nTraining resolution\nMulti-resolution performance (T op-1 Acc)\nAPE\nRoPE-Mixed\nSpiral RoPE (ours)\n(a)DeiT-Base\n144 192 224 256 320 384 448 512\nInput resolution\n78\n80\n82\n84T op-1 Accuracy (%)\nTraining resolution\nMulti-resolution performance (T op-1 Acc)\nAPE\nRoPE-Mixed\nSpiral RoPE (ours)\n(b)DeiT-Large\nFigure 4.Multi-resolution performance on ImageNet-1k. Models\nare trained at 224×224 and evaluated across resolutions from\n144×144 to 512×512 . Spiral RoPE demonstrates superior\nrobustness to resolution changes compared to APE and RoPE-\nMixed baselines across both model sizes.\nTable 2.ADE20k semantic segmentation results.All models are\npretrained on ImageNet-1k and then fintuned with an UperNet\nsegmentation head for 160k iterations at512×512resolution.\nBACKBONEMETHOD MIOUMACC AACC\nDEIT-S APE 43.72 54.33 81.07\nSPIRALROPE45.44 56.33 81.61\nDEIT-B APE 46.89 57.28 82.30\nSPIRALROPE48.11 59.07 82.76\nDEIT-L APE 46.91 57.05 82.36\nSPIRALROPE49.12 60.11 83.40\nsuggesting that for dense prediction tasks such as semantic\nsegmentation where reasoning is more complex and higher\ninput resolutions are required, a well-designed relative posi-\ntion embedding can more effectively facilitate the modeling\nof spatial dependencies, demonstrating that Spiral RoPE\nconsistently delivers larger benefits on more challenging\ntasks.\n4.3. Image Generation\nSetup.We also evaluate Spiral RoPE on class-conditional\nimage generation using Diffusion Transformers (DiT) (?).\nWe train DiT models of various sizes (S, B, L, XL) with\npatch sizes of 2 (denoted as /2 in the original paper) on Ima-\ngeNet 256×256 . The /2 models process 128×128 latent\npatches (16×16 tokens after patchification). We useK= 8\n6\n330\n331\n332\n333\n334\n335\n336\n337\n338\n339\n340\n341\n342\n343\n344\n345\n346\n347\n348\n349\n350\n351\n352\n353\n354\n355\n356\n357\n358\n359\n360\n361\n362\n363\n364\n365\n366\n367\n368\n369\n370\n371\n372\n373\n374\n375\n376\n377\n378\n379\n380\n381\n382\n383\n384\nSpiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\nTable 3.Class-conditional image generationon ImageNet 256×\n256 using DiT. We compare models trained for 400k steps with\nthe standard training hyperparameters of DiT. We generate 50k\nsamples using DDPM sampling with 250 steps and classifier-free\nguidance scale of 1.0. Baseline results with supermarks * are taken\nfrom U-DiTs (?).\nMODELMETHODFID↓SFID↓IS↑PREC.↑REC.↑\nDIT-S/2 APE∗ 67.40 11.93 20.44 0.368 0.559\nSPIRALROPE63.33 11.91 21.96 0.386 0.574\nDIT-B/2 APE∗ 42.84 8.24 33.66 0.491 0.629\nSPIRALROPE37.74 8.23 38.31 0.520 0.630\nDIT-L/2 APE∗ 23.276.3559.63 0.6110.635\nSPIRALROPE19.026.3669.49 0.6380.632\nDIT-XL/2 APE∗ 20.05 6.25 66.74 0.632 0.629\nSPIRALROPE15.55 5.87 79.67 0.662 0.631\nTable 4.Extended training comparisonon ImageNet256×256.\nThe Spiral RoPE model uses DiT-XL/2 architecture trained for\n7M steps. We use classifier-free guidance with scale 1.5. Baseline\nresults are from SiT (?).\nMETHODFID↓SFID↓IS↑PREC.↑REC.↑\nDIT 2.27 4.60 278.24 0.83 0.57\nSIT 2.06 4.49 277.50 0.83 0.59\nSPIRALROPE (OURS)1.74 4.49 279.64 0.83 0.60\ndirections for S/B/L models and K= 6 for XL models. All\nmodels are trained for 400k steps with the original training\nrecipe of DiT (?). For evaluation, we generate 50k samples\nusing DDPM sampling with 250 steps and classifier-free\nguidance scale of 1.0, and compute Fr´echet Inception Dis-\ntance (FID) (?) against the ImageNet validation set statistics.\nAdditional training details are provided in Appendix A.\nResults.Table 3 presents the FID scores. The results sug-\ngest that Spiral RoPE is most effective when the sequence\nlength is sufficiently large for the multi-directional encoding\nto capture meaningful spatial relationships.\nExtended Training.To further demonstrate the effective-\nness of Spiral RoPE when scaled to longer training, we\nconduct experiments following the setup of SiT (?). Specif-\nically, we train the XL/2 models for 7 million steps on\nImageNet 256×256 and evaluate using classifier-free guid-\nance with scale 1.5. Table 4 compares our Spiral RoPE\nagainst the original DiT baseline and SiT. Our Spiral RoPE\nachieves an FID of 1.74, outperforming both DiT (2.27) and\nSiT (2.06). Figure 5 shows qualitative samples generated by\nour model.\n5. Analysis\nIn this section, we provide further analysis of Spiral RoPE,\nincluding visualization of attention maps and ablation stud-\nFigure 5.Generated samplesfrom our DiT-XL/2 model with\nSpiral RoPE trained for 7M steps on ImageNet 256×256 . Images\nare generated using classifier-free guidance with scale 4.0.\nies on key hyperparameters.\n5.1. Visualization of Attention Maps\nTo qualitatively understand the differences between posi-\ntional encoding methods, we visualize attention maps from\nDeiT-Base models fine-tuned at448×448 resolution. We\ncompare three variants: the original APE baseline, APE\nwith axial 2D RoPE, and APE with Spiral RoPE (K= 16 ).\nClass-Token Attention.We first visualize the class-token\nattention by averaging the attention weights over all heads\nin the last transformer layer. Figure 6 shows representative\nexamples from the ImageNet validation set. A clear progres-\nsion is visible across the three methods. The APE baseline\nproduces diffuse attention patterns, with substantial activa-\ntion spread across both foreground objects and background\nregions. Axial RoPE improves over APE by allocating\nstronger attention to semantically relevant regions; however,\nits attention maps still exhibit noticeable residual activations\nin surrounding background areas and irrelevant objects. In\ncontrast, Spiral RoPE yields the most object-centric and\nspatially coherent attention patterns, characterized by con-\ncentrated responses on the foreground objects and effective\nsuppression of background activations. This advantage is\nparticularly pronounced in multi-instance scenes, where Spi-\nral RoPE sharply attends to multiple relevant objects, while\nAxial RoPE still exhibits axis-aligned artifacts and attention\nleakage into nearby regions.\nQuery-Token Attention.To further examine how posi-\ntional encoding influences local spatial relationships, we vi-\nsualize attention patterns originating from individual patch\ntokens. Figure 3 shows representative examples in which\nthe query token (marked by a red box) is located on a fore-\n7\n385\n386\n387\n388\n389\n390\n391\n392\n393\n394\n395\n396\n397\n398\n399\n400\n401\n402\n403\n404\n405\n406\n407\n408\n409\n410\n411\n412\n413\n414\n415\n416\n417\n418\n419\n420\n421\n422\n423\n424\n425\n426\n427\n428\n429\n430\n431\n432\n433\n434\n435\n436\n437\n438\n439\nSpiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\nImage Input\n APE (original)\n Axial RoPE\n Spiral RoPE (ours)\nImage Input\n APE (original)\n Axial RoPE\n Spiral RoPE (ours)\nImage Input\n APE (original)\n Axial RoPE","numLines":400,"startLine":750,"totalLines":1705}}}
